"Ouellet V., Mingelbier M., Saint-Hilaire A., Morin J.","Frequency analysis as a tool for assessing adverse conditions during a massive Fish Kill in the St. Lawrence River, Canada",2010,"Water Quality Research Journal of Canada","45","1",,"47","57",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78649350000&partnerID=40&md5=f55421bd920ad3d4fdd6de526ced16e8","INRS - Centre Eau Terre Environnement and Canadian Rivers Institute, 490 de la Couronne, Québec, G1K 9A9, Canada; Ministère des ressources naturelles et de la faune du Québec, Service de la Faune Aquatique, Québec, Canada; Environnement Canada, Service Météorologique du Canada - Section Hydrologie, Québec, Canada","Ouellet, V., INRS - Centre Eau Terre Environnement and Canadian Rivers Institute, 490 de la Couronne, Québec, G1K 9A9, Canada; Mingelbier, M., Ministère des ressources naturelles et de la faune du Québec, Service de la Faune Aquatique, Québec, Canada; Saint-Hilaire, A., INRS - Centre Eau Terre Environnement and Canadian Rivers Institute, 490 de la Couronne, Québec, G1K 9A9, Canada; Morin, J., Environnement Canada, Service Météorologique du Canada - Section Hydrologie, Québec, Canada","During the summer of 2001, the largest fish kill in the recorded history of the St. Lawrence River occurred. More than 25,000 dead carp were recovered. Preliminary analyses suggested hydroclimatic factors may have triggered the fish kill. Long time series of hydroclimatic variables were available upstream and downstream from the study area. In order to investigate if hydroclimatic conditions were extreme during the summer of 2001, frequency analyses were performed on time series of air and water temperature, water level, and solar radiation. During this period, the daily maximum water temperature was abnormally high (return period of 47 years) relative to other years. Air temperature was also high (return period of 22 years) and water level was very low (return period of 67 years). Results showed that hydroclimatic forcings were acting at two different time scales. First, short-term extremes are more likely to have direct impacts on ecosystems, such as lethal stress caused by oxygen depletion in shallow areas. Long-term extremes have indirect effects, which are more difficult to detect, such as immunosuppression. These results reiterate the importance of water temperature in aquatic habitat, particularly in the present context of global warming and climate change. © 2010, CAWQ.","Fish kill; Frequency analysis; Physiological stress; St. Lawrence River; Water temperature","Fish kills; Frequency analysis; Physiological stress; St. Lawrence River; Water temperature; Ecology; Fish; Global warming; Ocean habitats; Oxygen; Physiology; Sun; Temperature; Time series; Water levels; Rivers; air temperature; climate change; climate forcing; cyprinid; environmental stress; frequency analysis; freshwater ecosystem; mass mortality; physiological response; return period; solar radiation; time series; water level; water temperature; Canada; Saint Lawrence River; Cyprinidae",,,,,,"Akaike, H., A new look at the statistical model identification (1974) IEEE Trans. Autom. Control., 1, pp. 716-723; Bartholow, J.M., A Modeling Assessment of the Thermal Regime for an Urban Sport Fishery (1991) Environ. Manage., 15, pp. 833-845; Beer, W.N., Anderson, J.J., Effect of spawning day and temperature on salmon emergence: Interpretations of a growth model for Methow River Chinook (2001) Can. J. Fish. Aquat. Sci., 58, pp. 943-949; Beitinger, T.L., Bennett, W.A., Quantification of the role of acclimation temperature in temperature tolerance of fishes (2000) Environ. Biol. Fishes., 58, pp. 277-288; Bennett, W.A., Beitinger, T.L., McCauley, R.W., Rates of gain and loss of heat tolerance in channel catfish (1998) Trans. Am. Fish. Soc., 127, pp. 1051-1058; Bergstedt, R., Argyle, R.L., Seelye, J.G., Scribner, K.T., Curtis, G.L., In Situ Determination of the Annual Thermal Habitat Use by Lake Trout (Salvinus namayc